  <content>
    <title>Agentic RAG — Query Decomposition</title>

    <summary>A planning agent decomposes a complex query into 2–4 atomic sub-queries that can each be answered with a single retrieval call. Independent sub-queries run in parallel; results are merged and passed to the generator. This pattern maps directly to the "plan" node in a LangGraph agentic RAG workflow.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Complex questions like "Compare the regulatory approach in the EU and US for LLM-generated content and explain how it affects deployment timelines" cannot be answered by a single vector search — the relevant chunks exist under entirely different topics. Decomposing into sub-queries ("EU LLM regulation", "US LLM regulation", "regulatory impact on deployment timelines") lets each retrieval call be tuned to a single atomic information need, dramatically improving recall.</p>
      <p>Running independent sub-queries in parallel also reduces wall-clock latency compared to serial iterative retrieval, making decomposition the preferred pattern when the sub-queries are known upfront rather than discovered iteratively.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>The user query contains multiple distinct information needs (comparison, multi-part, "and also" structure).</item>
        <item>Multi-hop QA: the answer requires combining facts from disjoint documents.</item>
        <item>Research synthesis where the question has a known structure (e.g., compare A vs B across dimensions C, D, E).</item>
        <item>Legal compliance or fact-checking where exhaustive coverage of multiple sub-topics is required.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple factual lookups — decomposition adds an extra LLM call with no benefit.</item>
        <item>Queries with a single clear information need — decompose into one sub-query is a no-op and wastes a round-trip.</item>
        <item>When the sub-queries are not known upfront but emerge from retrieved context — use iterative retrieval instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="decomposition-pattern">
      <p>The decomposer makes a single LLM call to break the query into 2–4 atomic sub-queries returned as a JSON array. Each sub-query is then independently sent to the vector store. Results are merged and deduplicated before synthesis.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Sub-query decomposition MUST produce 2–4 sub-queries. If the LLM returns fewer than 2, treat the original query as atomic and fall back to single-pass RAG. If it returns more than 4, keep only the 4 highest-confidence sub-queries.</statement>
        <rationale>Fewer than 2 sub-queries means the original question was already atomic; more than 4 leads to redundant overlapping retrievals that inflate token usage and context length without improving coverage.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run independent sub-queries in parallel (e.g., via asyncio.gather or a thread pool). Cache sub-query results within a single agentic run — the same sub-query may recur across planning iterations.</statement>
        <rationale>Sub-queries are independent by construction; serial execution adds one round-trip latency per sub-query unnecessarily. Caching prevents duplicate retrieval calls when the same sub-query is generated in a later refinement cycle.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Track sub-query coverage: each sub-query MUST retrieve at least 1 high-confidence chunk (score above retrieval threshold). If a sub-query returns zero high-confidence chunks, flag it for query expansion rather than silently dropping it.</statement>
        <rationale>Silent coverage gaps produce answers that look complete but are missing entire information domains. Explicit flagging surfaces corpus holes for human review or corpus update.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="QueryDecomposer class">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from typing import List, Dict
import openai
import json

class QueryDecomposer:
    """Break complex queries into sub-queries."""

    def decompose(self, query: str) -> List[str]:
        """Decompose into atomic sub-queries."""
        prompt = f"""
Decompose this complex query into 2-4 simpler sub-queries that can
be answered independently:

Query: {query}

Return sub-queries as a JSON array of strings.
"""
        response = openai.chat.completions.create(
            model="gpt-4o-mini",
            messages=[{"role": "user", "content": prompt}],
            response_format={"type": "json_object"},
            temperature=0
        )

        result = json.loads(response.choices[0].message.content)
        return result.get("sub_queries", [query])

    def retrieve_for_subqueries(
        self,
        sub_queries: List[str],
        vector_store
    ) -> Dict[str, List[Dict]]:
        """Retrieve context for each sub-query."""
        results = {}
        for sq in sub_queries:
            results[sq] = vector_store.search(sq, k=5)
        return results
]]></code>
        <note>Use gpt-4o-mini (or Haiku) for decomposition; it is a classification task that does not require heavy reasoning.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="langgraph-plan-node">
      <p>In a LangGraph workflow, query decomposition maps to the "plan" node. The agent state carries the sub-queries list, and the retrieve node fans out over it.</p>

      <example type="good" title="LangGraph plan + retrieve nodes">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from langgraph.graph import Graph, END
from typing import TypedDict, List, Dict

class AgentState(TypedDict):
    query: str
    sub_queries: List[str]
    context: List[Dict]
    answer: str
    verified: bool

def plan(state: AgentState) -> AgentState:
    """Decompose query."""
    decomposer = QueryDecomposer()
    state["sub_queries"] = decomposer.decompose(state["query"])
    return state

def retrieve(state: AgentState) -> AgentState:
    """Retrieve for all sub-queries."""
    all_context = []
    for sq in state["sub_queries"]:
        chunks = vector_store.search(sq, k=5)
        all_context.extend(chunks)
    state["context"] = all_context
    return state

workflow = Graph()
workflow.add_node("plan", plan)
workflow.add_node("retrieve", retrieve)
workflow.set_entry_point("plan")
workflow.add_edge("plan", "retrieve")
]]></code>
        <note>The retrieve node extends context from all sub-queries; deduplication should happen before passing to the generator.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow-overview">
      <p>The full agentic RAG architecture that decomposition fits into: the planner subagent decomposes the query into 2–4 atomic sub-queries; the retriever subagent executes each sub-query against the vector store (in parallel where sub-queries are independent); a sufficiency judge evaluates whether the combined context answers the original question; if not, it generates a gap-filling refined query and triggers another retrieval round (max 3 rounds); the generator subagent synthesizes the final answer; a verifier subagent checks faithfulness against source chunks and flags ungrounded claims.</p>

      <section name="recommended-subagents">
        <p>Recommended subagents: query-planner (decomposes complex query into atomic sub-queries; returns JSON array), iterative-retriever (retrieves, evaluates sufficiency, and refines query in a bounded loop), rag-generator (synthesizes grounded answer from multi-hop context), faithfulness-verifier (checks each claim in the answer against retrieved sources; flags hallucinations).</p>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sub-query decomposition produces overlapping sub-queries (e.g., "EU AI regulation" and "EU AI Act regulations") that retrieve nearly identical chunks.</description>
        <reason>Overlapping sub-queries inflate context length and token costs without adding information. Use chunk deduplication by ID after retrieval. Consider generating sub-query embeddings and filtering out pairs with cosine similarity above 0.85.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Passing all sub-query results to the generator as separate context blocks without merging.</description>
        <reason>The generator receives fragmented context and may answer each sub-query independently rather than synthesizing a unified answer. Merge and deduplicate all chunks into a single context list before synthesis.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

